[4] SBV name dispute
Date: Sat, 28 Jan 2012
Source: Agrarisch Dagblad [Transl, summarised, edited]
http://www.agd.nl/Artikel/580079/Schmallenberg-wil-nieuwe-naam-voor-virus.htm?nb=agd&editie=28%20januari%202012&link=Schmallenberg%20wil%20nieuwe%20naam%20voor%20virus&WT.mc_id=mail_agd_28%20januari%202012

The virus that is circulating in sheep, goats and cattle, is named after the German town Schmallenberg where the virus was first detected. The ski resort is far from being happy about the name given to the virus; the residents want to get the virus renamed.

"The offense is great," said a spokesman for the city on Saturday [28 Jan 2012] There is therefore a request to the German Friedrich Loffler Institute (FLI) for the name to be modified. According to the institute, it is common for a virus to be named after the location where it was first detected [an example is the Akabane virus, after the t location in Japan where it was initially isolated].

--
